# Allowlist entries for scripts/launch-grep-scrub.sh.
#
# One regex per line, matching against the `<file>:<line>:<text>` shape
# git grep produces. Comment lines (starting with #) and blank lines are
# skipped. Each entry MUST have a comment above it explaining why the
# match is benign.

# DECISIONS.md and SPEC files contain the historical record of the
# closed-source-through-v1 lock and its rescission. These are
# legitimate references to the pre-2026-04-23 state of the project.
^DECISIONS\.md:.*(closed-source|closed-development|NDA|external contributions paused|v1 public-repo opening|lhassa8)
^docs/specs/.*\.md:.*(closed-source|closed-development|NDA|external contributions paused|v1 public-repo opening|lhassa8)
^CLAUDE\.md:.*(closed-source|closed-development|NDA|lhassa8)

# docs/launch/* are the launch-rehearsal artifacts. They legitimately
# reference the pre-launch state and historical context.
# NOTE: `lhassa8` deliberately NOT in this broad pattern. The runbook is
# operational — once the repo transfer happens, any lhassa8 reference in
# the runbook is a bug, not a historical note. The grep-scrub-checklist
# legitimately mentions lhassa8 (it documents what to look for) but is
# allowlisted by file path further down.
^docs/launch/.*\.md:.*(closed-source|closed-development|NDA|private)

# CONTRIBUTING.md historical CoC formal-process note legitimately
# discusses what's coming pre-launch.
^CONTRIBUTING\.md:.*(closed-source|NDA)

# README "Status" blockquote and Install section legitimately reference
# the pre-launch state.
^README\.md:.*(pre-launch private|closed-source-through-v1|closed-source lock)

# THREAT_MODEL.md T8 "malicious PR" mitigation legitimately discusses
# the closed-source-era posture for context.
^THREAT_MODEL\.md:.*(closed-source|NDA|private)

# LIMITATIONS.md install-gate language legitimately references the
# rescinded gating to provide historical context.
^LIMITATIONS\.md:.*(closed-source lock|private)

# docs/dual_horizon_plan.md and docs/icp.md carry historical
# scope-lock language for traceability.
^docs/dual_horizon_plan\.md:.*(closed-source|closed-development|NDA)
^docs/icp\.md:.*(closed-source|NDA)

# scan-action repo source ref carries the NDA-era acceptance criteria
# in the SPEC-07 comment block. Legitimate historical context.
^docs/specs/SPEC-07\.md:.*(NDA|closed-source)

# docs/RELEASE.md release-notes template references the verification
# instructions including signing identity strings.
^docs/RELEASE\.md:.*(efterlev/efterlev|closed-source|private)

# Historical references in COMPETITIVE_LANDSCAPE.md to competitor
# positioning may legitimately mention "private" companies, etc.
^COMPETITIVE_LANDSCAPE\.md:.*\bprivate\b

# Stale-test-count check is intentionally aggressive. The launch
# runbook (SPEC-56.2) calls out updating these in README.md before
# flipping public; allowlist any historical references in DECISIONS.md
# and SPEC files where the count was captured at the time.
^DECISIONS\.md:.*(279|344|461|496|529|552|575|602) (test|passing)
^docs/specs/.*\.md:.*(279|344|461|496|529|552|575|602) (test|passing)

# "Confidentiality" appears legitimately in CIA-triad and FRMR
# definitions (SC-28 mapping precedent, transmission-confidentiality
# KSI, FRMR security-event definitions). The internal_only_markers
# check is intended for DND/confidential document headers, not for
# the technical vocabulary of compliance frameworks.
.*[Cc]onfidentiality
^DECISIONS\.md:.*[Cc]onfidential
^LIMITATIONS\.md:.*[Cc]onfidential
^CLAUDE\.md:.*(279|344|461|496|529|552|575|602) (test|passing)

# Vendored NIST 800-53 Rev 5 catalog contains "confidential" in
# legitimate compliance-framework prose (e.g., AC-16 enhancement
# discussing classification labels: "top secret, secret, confidential,
# controlled unclassified"). This is upstream NIST content, not a
# document-confidentiality marker.
^catalogs/nist/.*\.json:.*[Cc]onfidential

# The grep-scrub-checklist.md file documents what the script checks
# for, so it legitimately mentions the very strings the
# internal_only_markers pattern is hunting (e.g., "confidential",
# "internal only", "do not distribute") inside its own description.
^docs/launch/grep-scrub-checklist\.md:

# docs/security-review-2026-04.md legitimately references the
# pending repo transfer from `lhassa8/Efterlev` → `efterlev/efterlev`
# in §6 (public-repo posture) as a maintainer-action callout. This
# is forward-looking historical context, not a stale reference.
^docs/security-review-2026-04\.md:.*lhassa8
